{"blocks":[{"key":"4rinc","text":"Docker is a tool designed to make it easier to create, deploy, and run applications by using containers. Containers allow a developer to package up an application with all of the parts it needs, such as libraries and other dependencies, and ship it all out as one package. By doing so, thanks to the container, the developer can rest assured that the application will run on any other Linux machine regardless of any customized settings that machine might have that could differ from the machine used for writing and testing the code.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"offset":0,"length":534,"style":"color-rgb(68,68,68)"},{"offset":0,"length":534,"style":"bgcolor-rgb(244,244,244)"},{"offset":0,"length":534,"style":"fontsize-18"},{"offset":0,"length":534,"style":"fontfamily-Swiss 721 SWA", "Helvetica Neue", Helvetica, Arial, "Nimbus Sans L", sans-serif"},{"offset":0,"length":6,"style":"color-rgb(0,152,195)"}],"entityRanges":[{"offset":0,"length":6,"key":0}],"data":{"text-align":"start"}},{"key":"ecu54","text":"Who is Docker for?","type":"header-two","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"offset":0,"length":18,"style":"color-rgb(68,68,68)"},{"offset":0,"length":18,"style":"bgcolor-rgb(244,244,244)"},{"offset":0,"length":18,"style":"fontsize-1.4em"},{"offset":0,"length":18,"style":"fontfamily-Swiss 721 SWA", "Helvetica Neue", Helvetica, Arial, "Nimbus Sans L", sans-serif"}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{"text-align":"start"}},{"key":"ndss","text":"Docker is a tool that is designed to benefit both developers and system administrators, making it a part of many DevOps (developers + operations) toolchains. For developers, it means that they can focus on writing code without worrying about the system that it will ultimately be running on. It also allows them to get a head start by using one of thousands of programs already designed to run in a Docker container as a part of their application. For operations staff, Docker gives flexibility and potentially reduces the number of systems needed because of its small footprint and lower overhead.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"offset":0,"length":598,"style":"color-rgb(68,68,68)"},{"offset":0,"length":598,"style":"bgcolor-rgb(244,244,244)"},{"offset":0,"length":598,"style":"fontsize-18"},{"offset":0,"length":598,"style":"fontfamily-Swiss 721 SWA", "Helvetica Neue", Helvetica, Arial, "Nimbus Sans L", sans-serif"}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{"text-align":"start"}},{"key":"c1ak3","text":"Getting started","type":"header-two","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"offset":0,"length":15,"style":"color-rgb(68,68,68)"},{"offset":0,"length":15,"style":"bgcolor-rgb(244,244,244)"},{"offset":0,"length":15,"style":"fontsize-1.4em"},{"offset":0,"length":15,"style":"fontfamily-Swiss 721 SWA", "Helvetica Neue", Helvetica, Arial, "Nimbus Sans L", sans-serif"}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{"text-align":"start"}},{"key":"3mc79","text":"Here are some resources that will help you get started using Docker in your workflow. Docker provides a web-based tutorial with a command-line simulator that you can try out basic Docker commands with and begin to understand how it works. There is also a beginners guide to Docker that introduces you to some basic commands and container terminology. Or watch the video below for a more in-depth look.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"offset":0,"length":103,"style":"color-rgb(68,68,68)"},{"offset":104,"length":18,"style":"color-rgb(68,68,68)"},{"offset":123,"length":131,"style":"color-rgb(68,68,68)"},{"offset":255,"length":25,"style":"color-rgb(68,68,68)"},{"offset":281,"length":120,"style":"color-rgb(68,68,68)"},{"offset":0,"length":103,"style":"bgcolor-rgb(244,244,244)"},{"offset":104,"length":18,"style":"bgcolor-rgb(244,244,244)"},{"offset":123,"length":131,"style":"bgcolor-rgb(244,244,244)"},{"offset":255,"length":25,"style":"bgcolor-rgb(244,244,244)"},{"offset":281,"length":120,"style":"bgcolor-rgb(244,244,244)"},{